name ltx-talk
category Package
revision 78858
shortdesc A class for typesetting presentations
longdesc This class is experimental, and changes may occur to
longdesc interfaces. Development is focussed on tagging/functionality as
longdesc the primary driver; as such, support for design aspects is
longdesc likely to be lower priority. It requires LaTeX 2025-11-01 or
longdesc later. The ltx-talk class is focused on producing (on-screen)
longdesc presentations, along with support material such as handouts and
longdesc speaker notes. Content is created in a frame environment, each
longdesc of which can be divided up into a number of slides (actual
longdesc output pages). A simple 'overlay' notation is used to specify
longdesc which material appears on each slide within a frame. The class
longdesc supports a range of environments to enable complex slide
longdesc relationships to be constructed. The appearance of slides is
longdesc controlled by a template system. Many of the elements of slides
longdesc can be adjusted by setting simple key-based values in the
longdesc preamble. More complex changes can be implemented by altering
longdesc specific, targeted definitions without needing to rewrite
longdesc entire blocks of code. This allows a variety of visual
longdesc appearances to be selected for the same content source. The
longdesc ltx-talk class has syntax similar to the popular beamer class,
longdesc although there are some (deliberate) differences. However,
longdesc ltx-talk has been implemented to support creation of tagged
longdesc (accessible) PDF output as a core aim. As such, it is suited to
longdesc creating output for reuse in other formats, e.g. HTML
longdesc conversions, without additional steps.
